2.body: Imagine you know a secret password, but you want to prove you know it without revealing the password itself . This is the essence of zero-knowledge proofs. Formal definition : A zero-knowledge proof is a cryptographic method where one party (the prover) can convince another party (the verifier) that a statement is true, without revealing any information beyond the truth of the statement itself.
2.title: What Are Zero-Knowledge Proofs?

25.body: A field is a mathematical structure where you can add, subtract, multiply, and divide (except by zero). Examples you know: Rational numbers (‚Ñö): fractions like 3/4, -5/7 Real numbers (‚Ñù): decimals like 3.14, ‚àö2 Complex numbers (‚ÑÇ): a + bi

26.body: In cryptography, we use finite fields - fields with a finite number of elements. We denote a field of prime order p as ùîΩ‚Çö . Example : ùîΩ‚Çá = {0, 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6} (integers modulo 7)
26.title: Finite Fields (Galois Fields)

27.body:
Finite fields use modular arithmetic - arithmetic that wraps around. // In ùîΩ‚Çá:
(5 + 4) % 7 = 9 % 7 = 2 // Addition wraps around
(3 √ó 6) % 7 = 18 % 7 = 4 // Multiplication wraps around Key intuition : Think of a clock (modular arithmetic mod 12): 10:00 + 5 hours = 3:00 (not 15:00!) 9:00 - 12 hours = 9:00 (going backwards wraps)
27.title: Modular Arithmetic

28.body:
In our Rust code, we use ark_bn254::Fr - the scalar field for BN254 elliptic curve: use ark_bn254::Fr as ScalarField;
use ark_ff::Field; // Field elements
let a = ScalarField::from(5u64);
let b = ScalarField::from(4u64); let sum = a + b; // Addition
let product = a * b; // Multiplication
let inverse = a.inverse().unwrap(); // Multiplicative inverse
let square = a.square(); // Exponentiation (a¬≤) // All operations are modulo the field prime (automatically!) Run this example : cargo run --example field_operations

3.body: Think of the "Where's Waldo?" puzzle: You find Waldo quickly. You want to prove to your friend you found him, but you don't want to reveal his location (spoiling the fun). Zero-knowledge solution : You (prover) find Waldo You cover the page with a large piece of cardboard with a small cutout You position the cutout over Waldo so only Waldo is visible Your friend (verifier) sees Waldo through the hole Your friend is convinced Waldo exists on the page But your friend learns nothing about Waldo's location! This captures the three properties of zero-knowledge proofs: Completeness : If Waldo is really there, your friend will be convinced Soundness : If Waldo isn't there, you can't fake the proof Zero-knowledge : Your friend learns only that Waldo exists, not where
3.title: Real-World Analogy: Where's Waldo?

30.body: A polynomial is an expression of variables and coefficients: P(x) = a‚ÇÄ + a‚ÇÅx + a‚ÇÇx¬≤ + a‚ÇÉx¬≥ + ... + a‚Çôx‚Åø Where: a·µ¢ are coefficients (from a field) x is the variable n is the degree Example : P(x) = 2 + 3x + x¬≤ is a degree-2 polynomial
30.breadcrumbs: Mathematical Background ¬ª What is a Polynomial?
30.title: What is a Polynomial?

31.body: Polynomials are incredibly useful in zero-knowledge proofs because of this fundamental theorem : Theorem : A degree-d polynomial is uniquely determined by d+1 points. Implication : If two degree-d polynomials agree on d+1 points, they're identical! This is the foundation of QAP (Quadratic Arithmetic Programs).
31.title: Why Polynomials?

32.title: Polynomial Evaluation

33.body:
Interpolation is the reverse of evaluation: given points, find the polynomial. Lagrange Interpolation finds the unique polynomial passing through given points: Given: (1, 3), (2, 5), (3, 9)
Find: P(x) such that P(1)=3, P(2)=5, P(3)=9 Formula : For points (x‚ÇÅ, y‚ÇÅ), ..., (x‚Çô, y‚Çô): P(x) = Œ£ y·µ¢ ¬∑ L·µ¢(x) Where L·µ¢(x) is the i-th Lagrange basis polynomial: L·µ¢(x) = Œ† (x - x‚±º) / (x·µ¢ - x‚±º) for all j ‚â† i Example (simplified): Given points (1, 3), (2, 5): L‚ÇÅ(x) = (x - 2) / (1 - 2) = (x - 2) / -1 = 2 - x
L‚ÇÇ(x) = (x - 1) / (2 - 1) = (x - 1) / 1 = x - 1 P(x) = 3¬∑L‚ÇÅ(x) + 5¬∑L‚ÇÇ(x) = 3(2 - x) + 5(x - 1) = 6 - 3x + 5x - 5 = 1 + 2x Verify: P(1) = 1 + 2(1) = 3 ‚úì P(2) = 1 + 2(2) = 5 ‚úì

36.body: A key insight in Groth16: A polynomial is divisible by another if and only if it evaluates to zero at all roots of the divisor . Example : Let T(x) = (x - 1)(x - 2)(x - 3) (a "target polynomial") If P(x) = H(x) ¬∑ T(x), then: P(1) = H(1) ¬∑ T(1) = H(1) ¬∑ 0 = 0 P(2) = H(2) ¬∑ T(2) = H(2) ¬∑ 0 = 0 P(3) = H(3) ¬∑ T(3) = H(3) ¬∑ 0 = 0 Converse : If P(1) = P(2) = P(3) = 0, then P(x) is divisible by T(x)! This is the QAP satisfaction check in Groth16!

4.title: Why Groth16?

40.body: For a √ó b = c: R1CS form : Az ‚àò Bz = Cz where z = [1, a, b, c] QAP form : P(x) = H(x) ¬∑ T(x) where P(x) = A(x) ¬∑ B(x) - C(x) Verification : Check if P(x) is divisible by T(x) using pairings We'll see this in detail in Chapters 2 and 3!

5.body: Tiny proofs : Only 128 bytes (regardless of circuit complexity!) Fast verification : Constant-time verification with pairings Widely deployed : Used by Zcash, Ethereum (Tornado Cash), and more Battle-tested : Years of real-world use with no breaks
5.title: Key Advantages

6.body: Trusted setup : Requires a one-time setup ceremony with "toxic waste" Per-circuit keys : Each circuit needs its own proving/verification keys Not universal : Unlike newer protocols (PLONK, Halo 2), Groth16 requires circuit-specific setup
6.title: Trade-offs
